                        <div class="post-heading">
                            <h1>What steps can we take to help</h1>
                            <h2 class="subheading">Animals in zoos are highly mistreated.They are put in cages away from their natural habitats and used for monetary gains.</h2>
                            <span class="meta">
                                Posted by
                                <a href="#!">Carson Stang</a>
                                on April 28, 2023
                            </span>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
        </header>
        <!-- Post Content-->
        <article class="mb-4">
            <div class="container px-4 px-lg-5">
                <div class="row gx-4 gx-lg-5 justify-content-center">
                    <div class="col-md-10 col-lg-8 col-xl-7">
                        <p>The issue of zoos and animal captivity is a complex one, with valid arguments on both sides. Some animal rights activists argue that zoos deprive animals of their natural rights and can cause stress, boredom, and illness. Critics also question the effectiveness of zoos in contributing to animal conservation, arguing that they may prioritize entertainment over true conservation efforts.
                        <p>However, some experts argue that zoos play a critical role in preserving endangered species and furthering scientific research. Zoos can provide a safe haven for animals at risk of extinction, and researchers can study animal behavior and genetics to aid in conservation efforts. Furthermore, zoos can serve as an educational tool for raising awareness and inspiring action to protect wildlife and their habitats.
                        <p>Ultimately, whether zoos are ethical or not depends on how they are managed and the priority placed on animal welfare and conservation efforts.

                        <h2 class="section-heading">How Do We Fix Zoo's?</h2>
                        <iframe width="560" height="315" src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/05nDoxdSzwY" title="YouTube video player" frameborder="0" allow="accelerometer; autoplay; clipboard-write; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture; web-share" allowfullscreen></iframe>
                        <span class="caption text-muted">This is how you add captions under a video or image. Cite your video/image here. You may also say something about it, if you like.</span>
                        <p>Throughout the history of zoos there has been evidence of severe boredom in zoos affecting the animals that call them home. Many zoo animals show signs of boredom and stress such as head bobbing and swaying.</p>
                        <p>The feelings of animals needs to be introduced to children when they start going to zoos as it is important that when a person thinks of zoos they have a greater understanding of the boredom and emotions that must be going through an animal's head as it is being watched while it probably feels trapped and anxious in their enclosures. Zoo’s would need to change if people stopped visiting and they stopped getting money. Now i’m not saying stop going because that would affect the animals, but we need to speak up against the cruelty some animals experience. The best way to help them is to bring awareness to the problem and push for legislation to create ‘bare minimum’ requirements to be humane.</p>
                            Information by 
                            <a href="#!">Adrienne kennedy</a>
